            "chars": "<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\"><em><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">DC.X.R4</span></em></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">&ldquo;Never more to touch that passive hand&rdquo;</span></strong></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\"><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Calibri,sans-serif; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">This entry refers to David&rsquo;s observation of the sleeping Steerforth, \"lying, easily, with his head upon his arm, as I had often seen him lie at school&rdquo; (DC 443). The line is given with greater emotion in the published text: &ldquo;&mdash;Never more, oh God forgive you, Steerforth! to touch that passive hand in love or friendship. Never, never, more!&rdquo; (DC 444).&nbsp;</span><span id=\"docs-internal-guid-822bbdde-7fff-7a35-8687-2e1512144103\"></span></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\"><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Calibri,sans-serif; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">David again recollects the memory of Steerforth sleeping after his death in No. XVII, and it is possible that its inclusion on the Working Note facilitated the reiteration of the image: &ldquo;among the ruins of the home he had wronged&mdash;I saw [Steerforth] lying with his head upon his arm, as I had often seen him lie at school&rdquo; (DC 801).&nbsp;</span></p>"
